Rubber duck debugging is about narrating your code to an imaginary audience. Example: if your Java app throws NullPointerException, you might write:
```java
try {
    someObject.method();
} catch (NullPointerException e) {
    System.out.println("Duck says: " + e.getMessage());
}
```
If it prints nothing, the duck is missing. It forces you to verbalize assumptions and reveals hidden bugs.

So maybe I need a real user asking me questions instead of printing?

